explores the rhetoric of politicians, who have used the language of fascism to smear opponents, and he looks at the discussions of pundits, the analyses of academics, and the displays of fascism in popular culture, including fiction, radio, TV, theater, and film. Kuklick argues that fascism has little informational meaning in the United States, but instead, it is used to denigrate or insult. For example, every political position has been besmirched as fascist. As a result, the term does not describe a phenomenon so much as it denounces what one does not like. Finally, in displaying fascism for most Americans, entertainment—and most importantly film—has been crucial in conveying to citizens what fascism is about. Fascism Comes to America has been enhanced by many illustrations that exhibit how fascism was absorbed into the US public consciousness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aFascismzUnited States. 0aLanguage and languagesxPolitical aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  apopular culture, rhetoric, politics, government, politicians, denigration, nonfiction, mussolini, italy, hitler, germany, mudslinging, political opponents, pundits, entertainment, film, television, radio, theater, insult, denounce, ideology, public opinion, repression, oppression, resistance, dictator, control, fear, paranoia, free speech, injustice.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226822457423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226822457/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles